\par \pard\plain \s0\sl276\slmult1\ql\aspalpha\faauto\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi0\sb0\sa0\ltrpar\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf1\striked0\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\hich\af2\dbch\af2\afs22\ai0\ab0\langfe1033\lang1033\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033{\lang1025\rtlch \ltrch\loch
What is the general technique employed here?}
\par \pard\plain \s0\sl276\slmult1\ql\aspalpha\faauto\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi0\sb0\sa0\ltrpar\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf1\striked0\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\hich\af2\dbch\af2\afs22\ai0\ab0\langfe1033\lang1033\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033{\listtext\pard\plain \cf1\ulnone\ulc0 \u9679\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls2 \li360\ri0\lin360\rin0\fi-360\tx1080\li1080\ri0\lin1080\rin0\fi-360{\lang1025\rtlch \ltrch\loch
The general idea is to first do the best we can with simulations, then build a test rig and then try various fans with a reasonably intelligent approach (better than brute force) to see which gives the best noise and flow/pressure.  To simplify things, I picked one RPM, 300, and optimized to get better results at that point. Now I\'92m usually using 400 rpm because it\'92s quiet enough at that speed, so optimizing again for that RPM might yield improvement. Unfortunately this is not actualy that easy as the only practical way to know how much noise one aspect is contributing is by eliminating it.  So the motor for instance, you have to make that quiet before you can get far on the blades.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\sl276\slmult1\ql\aspalpha\faauto\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi0\sb0\sa0\ltrpar\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf1\striked0\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\hich\af2\dbch\af2\afs22\ai0\ab0\langfe1033\lang1033\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033{\listtext\pard\plain \cf1\ulnone\ulc0 \u9675\'3f\tab}\ilvl1\ls2 \li360\ri0\lin360\rin0\fi-360\tx1800\li1800\ri0\lin1800\rin0\fi-360{\lang1025\rtlch \ltrch\loch
The optimization process involved binary searches and also looking in there with smoke etc. to see how the air was flowing around, listening to see if I could determine how the noise was being produced (easy to tell motor hum or blade buzz from the whoosh of the blades due to turbulence for instance). Then forming hypothesis, proving them and testing more.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\sl276\slmult1\ql\aspalpha\faauto\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi0\sb0\sa0\ltrpar\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf1\striked0\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\hich\af2\dbch\af2\afs22\ai0\ab0\langfe1033\lang1033\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033{\listtext\pard\plain \cf1\ulnone\ulc0 \u9675\'3f\tab}\ilvl1\ls2 \li360\ri0\lin360\rin0\fi-360\tx1800\li1800\ri0\lin1800\rin0\fi-360{\lang1025\rtlch \ltrch\loch
I make at least 52 unique prototypes, I think.  Some were not documented as they were uninteresting, like the one with the slightly defective frame that made a surprising amount of noise as a result.   By this I mean I often recycled parts to make new fans, including mixing various primaries and secondaries to see what worked better.  Different spacings between primary and secondary were also tried but I\'92m not including that in the total of 52.  There must have been hundreds of exact unique combinations tried.  The most important thing to document is when progress is made, but documenting everything is probably a good idea, as long as you can still find the good stuff. }
\par \pard\plain \s0\sl276\slmult1\ql\aspalpha\faauto\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi0\sb0\sa0\ltrpar\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf1\striked0\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\hich\af2\dbch\af2\afs22\ai0\ab0\langfe1033\lang1033\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033{\listtext\pard\plain \cf1\ulnone\ulc0 \u9675\'3f\tab}\ilvl1\ls2 \li360\ri0\lin360\rin0\fi-360\tx1800\li1800\ri0\lin1800\rin0\fi-360{\lang1025\rtlch \ltrch\loch
Obviously, back the best stuff up periodically and keep an orderly workplace etc.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\sl276\slmult1\ql\aspalpha\faauto\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi0\sb0\sa0\ltrpar\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf1\striked0\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\hich\af2\dbch\af2\afs22\ai0\ab0\langfe1033\lang1033\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033{\listtext\pard\plain \cf1\ulnone\ulc0 \u9679\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls2 \li360\ri0\lin360\rin0\fi-360\tx1080\li1080\ri0\lin1080\rin0\fi-360{\lang1025\rtlch \ltrch\loch
It\'92s also useful to note that MERV-13 filters may not be the optimal at these pressures and for these configurations.  There may be a significantly better filter/geometrical arrangement combo.  You\'92d have to go back and forth testing and improving both to work your way to a better air purifier if you wanted to optimize for both 400 rpm and different filters.  I used 10x merv-13 filters with the VVV in the middle (see bqap builds document).}
\par \pard\plain \s0\sl276\slmult1\ql\aspalpha\faauto\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi0\sb0\sa0\ltrpar\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf1\striked0\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\hich\af2\dbch\af2\afs22\ai0\ab0\langfe1033\lang1033\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033{\listtext\pard\plain \cf1\ulnone\ulc0 \u9679\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls2 \li360\ri0\lin360\rin0\fi-360\tx1080\li1080\ri0\lin1080\rin0\fi-360{\lang1025\rtlch \ltrch\loch
A primary blade that is relatively thick.  It imparts pressure to the air, and also rotational motion.  The pressure is directly useful, the rotational motion will be converted to pressure to some degree by the secondary.  Usually it\'92s just about pressure.  The thicker the blade disk (the cylinder around the blades) the better this works, but of course it\'92s a practical compromise with how large you want to let them be.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\sl276\slmult1\ql\aspalpha\faauto\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi0\sb0\sa0\ltrpar\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf1\striked0\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\hich\af2\dbch\af2\afs22\ai0\ab0\langfe1033\lang1033\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033{\listtext\pard\plain \cf1\ulnone\ulc0 \u9679\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls2 \li360\ri0\lin360\rin0\fi-360\tx1080\li1080\ri0\lin1080\rin0\fi-360{\lang1025\rtlch \ltrch\loch
A secondary blade, also called stator blades, which are stationary but the air is rotating relative to them, at a lower rpm however, than the primary relative to the air entering the fan.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\sl276\slmult1\ql\aspalpha\faauto\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi0\sb0\sa0\ltrpar\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf1\striked0\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\hich\af2\dbch\af2\afs22\ai0\ab0\langfe1033\lang1033\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033{\listtext\pard\plain \cf1\ulnone\ulc0 \u9679\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls2 \li360\ri0\lin360\rin0\fi-360\tx1080\li1080\ri0\lin1080\rin0\fi-360{\lang1025\rtlch \ltrch\loch
The primary and secondary are curved oppositely to each other, that is the spiral in the xy plane is opposite handedness.  This prevents the pressure wave emanating from the primary from slamming into the secondary all of a sudden, which produces a buzzing noise that we don\'92t want.  Many fans use struts that curve for this reason.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\sl276\slmult1\ql\aspalpha\faauto\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi0\sb0\sa0\ltrpar\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf1\striked0\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\hich\af2\dbch\af2\afs22\ai0\ab0\langfe1033\lang1033\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033{\listtext\pard\plain \cf1\ulnone\ulc0 \u9675\'3f\tab}\ilvl1\ls2 \li360\ri0\lin360\rin0\fi-360\tx1800\li1800\ri0\lin1800\rin0\fi-360{\lang1025\rtlch \ltrch\loch
The struts on some blades are also flat and slanted to reduce their cross section in the direction which the pressure wave propagates.  The secondary blades are to some degree like this automatically, although they can\'92t be minimal cross section of course.  But they are a lot better than flat bars.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\sl276\slmult1\ql\aspalpha\faauto\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi0\sb0\sa0\ltrpar\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf1\striked0\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\hich\af2\dbch\af2\afs22\ai0\ab0\langfe1033\lang1033\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033{\listtext\pard\plain \cf1\ulnone\ulc0 \u9679\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls2 \li360\ri0\lin360\rin0\fi-360\tx1080\li1080\ri0\lin1080\rin0\fi-360{\lang1025\rtlch \ltrch\loch
The blade number and curves of the primary and secondary are different, the de facto rpm is different so the optimal isn\'92t likely to be the same. }
\par \pard\plain \s0\sl276\slmult1\ql\aspalpha\faauto\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi0\sb0\sa0\ltrpar\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf1\striked0\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\hich\af2\dbch\af2\afs22\ai0\ab0\langfe1033\lang1033\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033{\listtext\pard\plain \cf1\ulnone\ulc0 \u9679\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls2 \li360\ri0\lin360\rin0\fi-360\tx1080\li1080\ri0\lin1080\rin0\fi-360{\lang1025\rtlch \ltrch\loch
Spacing between the primary and secondary turned out to be important.  Early prototypes did not work well as the spacing was too large.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\sl276\slmult1\ql\aspalpha\faauto\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi0\sb0\sa0\ltrpar\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf1\striked0\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\hich\af2\dbch\af2\afs22\ai0\ab0\langfe1033\lang1033\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033{\listtext\pard\plain \cf1\ulnone\ulc0 \u9679\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls2 \li360\ri0\lin360\rin0\fi-360\tx1080\li1080\ri0\lin1080\rin0\fi-360{\lang1025\rtlch \ltrch\loch
The thin wall on the outer edge of the blades is not strictly that helpful from a noise standpoint, I think, but it is important structurally, allowing the blades to be thinner, and thus easier to print and mold.   It also prevents them from flapping around, but to be honest I never tried any variants without it so I don\'92t know the impact it\'92s having for sure.  People think it reduces tip vortices, but I don\'92t think that\'92s likely to be a major factor here, that\'92s more of an issue at higher blade velocities.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\sl276\slmult1\ql\aspalpha\faauto\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi0\sb0\sa0\ltrpar\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf1\striked0\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\hich\af2\dbch\af2\afs22\ai0\ab0\langfe1033\lang1033\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033{\listtext\pard\plain \cf1\ulnone\ulc0 \u9679\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls2 \li360\ri0\lin360\rin0\fi-360\tx1080\li1080\ri0\lin1080\rin0\fi-360{\lang1025\rtlch \ltrch\loch
The spiral curvature (xy plane) and zy plane curvature of the blades,blade number for both the primary and secondary, thickness of the blade disk (thickness of the cylinders that surround the primary and secondary blades), hub diameter had to be adjusted to find something reasonably close to optimal.  Diameter was fixed but in another application you might want to optimize that too.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\sl276\slmult1\ql\aspalpha\faauto\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi0\sb0\sa0\ltrpar\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf1\striked0\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\hich\af2\dbch\af2\afs22\ai0\ab0\langfe1033\lang1033\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033{\listtext\pard\plain \cf1\ulnone\ulc0 \u9679\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls2 \li360\ri0\lin360\rin0\fi-360\tx1080\li1080\ri0\lin1080\rin0\fi-360{\lang1025\rtlch \ltrch\loch
The grille has to be adequately far away from the primary blades, otherwise it creates noise as the pressure waves slam into it.  This is why it\'92s not directly against the secondary, or integral with the secondary.  I found it had to be a separate component, which is unfortunate as it costs more.  Of course it can\'92t be too dense/thick elements as that would impede airflow, too.  Making it further away from the primary also reduces the density it has to have, allowing air to flow through it better.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\sl276\slmult1\ql\aspalpha\faauto\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi0\sb0\sa0\ltrpar\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf1\striked0\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\hich\af2\dbch\af2\afs22\ai0\ab0\langfe1033\lang1033\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033{\listtext\pard\plain \cf1\ulnone\ulc0 \u9679\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls2 \li360\ri0\lin360\rin0\fi-360\tx1080\li1080\ri0\lin1080\rin0\fi-360{\lang1025\rtlch \ltrch\loch
The polymer turned out to be important.  By coincidence I found some fans were quieter than others, and since I kept good notes (this is important, keep orderly notes and data) I was able to identify that it was the polymer used.  }
\par \pard\plain \s0\sl276\slmult1\ql\aspalpha\faauto\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi0\sb0\sa0\ltrpar\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf1\striked0\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\hich\af2\dbch\af2\afs22\ai0\ab0\langfe1033\lang1033\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033{\listtext\pard\plain \cf1\ulnone\ulc0 \u9679\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls2 \li360\ri0\lin360\rin0\fi-360\tx1080\li1080\ri0\lin1080\rin0\fi-360{\b\lang1025\ab\rtlch \ltrch\loch
The motor/drive solution:}
\par \pard\plain \s0\sl276\slmult1\ql\aspalpha\faauto\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi0\sb0\sa0\ltrpar\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf1\striked0\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\hich\af2\dbch\af2\afs22\ai0\ab0\langfe1033\lang1033\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033{\listtext\pard\plain \cf1\ulnone\ulc0 \u9675\'3f\tab}\ilvl1\ls2 \li360\ri0\lin360\rin0\fi-360\tx1800\li1800\ri0\lin1800\rin0\fi-360{\lang1025\rtlch \ltrch\loch
After realizing that stepper motors do actually have the required speed/torque characteristics, which is hard to get from other motors at a good price, I pursued the use of a stepper motor as a practical power producing motor}
\par \pard\plain \s0\sl276\slmult1\ql\aspalpha\faauto\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi0\sb0\sa0\ltrpar\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf1\striked0\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\hich\af2\dbch\af2\afs22\ai0\ab0\langfe1033\lang1033\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033{\listtext\pard\plain \cf1\ulnone\ulc0 \u9675\'3f\tab}\ilvl1\ls2 \li360\ri0\lin360\rin0\fi-360\tx1800\li1800\ri0\lin1800\rin0\fi-360{\lang1025\rtlch \ltrch\loch
The previous motor was an 11 pole pair motor.  A typical stepper is 50 pole pairs.  They are also bipolar rather than three phase.  Aside from this, driving them and their noise characteristics don\'92t have to be that different}
\par \pard\plain \s0\sl276\slmult1\ql\aspalpha\faauto\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi0\sb0\sa0\ltrpar\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf1\striked0\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\hich\af2\dbch\af2\afs22\ai0\ab0\langfe1033\lang1033\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033{\listtext\pard\plain \cf1\ulnone\ulc0 \u9675\'3f\tab}\ilvl1\ls2 \li360\ri0\lin360\rin0\fi-360\tx1800\li1800\ri0\lin1800\rin0\fi-360{\lang1025\rtlch \ltrch\loch
Everyone thinks steppers are inherently noisy and this is not entirely wrong, because of the high pole pair count. However whichever motor I use I would probably want vibration isolation, so if I have to isolate the stepper motor this isn\'92t that big a deal.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\sl276\slmult1\ql\aspalpha\faauto\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi0\sb0\sa0\ltrpar\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf1\striked0\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\hich\af2\dbch\af2\afs22\ai0\ab0\langfe1033\lang1033\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033{\listtext\pard\plain \cf1\ulnone\ulc0 \u9675\'3f\tab}\ilvl1\ls2 \li360\ri0\lin360\rin0\fi-360\tx1800\li1800\ri0\lin1800\rin0\fi-360{\lang1025\rtlch \ltrch\loch
After realizing the drive strategy was working particularly well, I tried to eliminate the buzzing noise with anti cogging. This did not go well. I spent  along time on it and got basically nothing for it.  It is not clear to me why it seems to be practically impossible to drive the motor with very little torque ripple.  I think it may involve some kind of excited oscillation.  There seems to be no electrical waveform that can be fed to the motor that leads to completely smooth motion.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\sl276\slmult1\ql\aspalpha\faauto\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi0\sb0\sa0\ltrpar\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf1\striked0\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\hich\af2\dbch\af2\afs22\ai0\ab0\langfe1033\lang1033\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033{\listtext\pard\plain \cf1\ulnone\ulc0 \u9675\'3f\tab}\ilvl1\ls2 \li360\ri0\lin360\rin0\fi-360\tx1800\li1800\ri0\lin1800\rin0\fi-360{\lang1025\rtlch \ltrch\loch
Therefore I decided to just suspend the motor so it can produce torque but the vibration is isolated.  This is inconvenient and adds cost, but again probably any motor would require something like it to some degree.  Going to town with it is not a whole lot worse than a little bit.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\sl276\slmult1\ql\aspalpha\faauto\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi0\sb0\sa0\ltrpar\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf1\striked0\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\hich\af2\dbch\af2\afs22\ai0\ab0\langfe1033\lang1033\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033{\listtext\pard\plain \cf1\ulnone\ulc0 \u9675\'3f\tab}\ilvl1\ls2 \li360\ri0\lin360\rin0\fi-360\tx1800\li1800\ri0\lin1800\rin0\fi-360{\lang1025\rtlch \ltrch\loch
The motor turned out to vibrate due to some kind of feed back loop combined with some harmonic resonance.  It was so severe that when allowed to vibrate due to the decoupling, it would stall at some speeds.  To dampen this, I added a flywheel made of a high damping polymer, 95A TPU.  I had some difficulty getting it to transmit enough torque, but eventually solved that.  This appears to reduce the oscillations at an even lower level.  This is what makes me think there is some kind of oscillation that is excited and part of a feedback loop.  I\'92d have to figure out the physics and math out a bit better to elucidate this (see where the gain coomes from eetc by modelling the system basically), but for now it works fine.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\sl276\slmult1\ql\aspalpha\faauto\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi0\sb0\sa0\ltrpar\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf1\striked0\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\hich\af2\dbch\af2\afs22\ai0\ab0\langfe1033\lang1033\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033{\listtext\pard\plain \cf1\ulnone\ulc0 \u9675\'3f\tab}\ilvl1\ls2 \li360\ri0\lin360\rin0\fi-360\tx1800\li1800\ri0\lin1800\rin0\fi-360{\lang1025\rtlch \ltrch\loch
The drive strategy is particularly curious.  It\'92s not actually open loop as we know it, there is no actual current regulation.  It\'92s only ramped voltage.  It works because the back emf goes down when the torque angle increases, which it increases with load.  If we apply a constant RMS voltage, thus the current actually compensates for higher load automatically. It just has to be in a suitable range for the rpm.   It could almost work without this, but having it is particularly helpful as it further increases safety margin against stall.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\sl276\slmult1\ql\aspalpha\faauto\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi0\sb0\sa0\ltrpar\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf1\striked0\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\hich\af2\dbch\af2\afs22\ai0\ab0\langfe1033\lang1033\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033{\listtext\pard\plain \cf1\ulnone\ulc0 \u9632\'3f\tab}\ilvl2\ls2 \li360\ri0\lin360\rin0\fi-180\tx2520\li2520\ri0\lin2520\rin0\fi-180{\lang1025\rtlch \ltrch\loch
There is a system in the driver for the more recent programs that uses a polynomial that predicts (measured) normal operating current.  If operating current is outside the range predicted, it shuts off the motor.  You have to power cycle it to resolve the situation.  In other words you need the user to come pay attention, which is what we want. If someone shoves something in the fan, it therefore shuts down automatically.  If it stalls for any reason like a wiring error, this system also trips.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\sl276\slmult1\ql\aspalpha\faauto\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi0\sb0\sa0\ltrpar\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf1\striked0\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\hich\af2\dbch\af2\afs22\ai0\ab0\langfe1033\lang1033\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033{\listtext\pard\plain \cf1\ulnone\ulc0 \u9632\'3f\tab}\ilvl2\ls2 \li360\ri0\lin360\rin0\fi-180\tx2520\li2520\ri0\lin2520\rin0\fi-180{\lang1025\rtlch \ltrch\loch
Thi strategy is mentioned in some old textbooks and for industrial motors but I haven\'92t sen it anywhere else.  I would simply describe it as voltage ramped synchronous drive.  Not open loop, open loop implies current regulation most of the time.}
