}
\par \pard\plain \s0\sl276\slmult1\ql\aspalpha\faauto\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi0\sb0\sa0\ltrpar\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf1\striked0\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\hich\af2\dbch\af2\afs22\ai0\ab0\langfe1033\lang1033\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033{\lang1025\rtlch \ltrch\loch
It\'92s worth noting that it\'92s probably possible to improve performance slightly further by further adjusting the curves and blade number, thickness of the blade disk, hub diameter etc.I am not immune to the reality which probably led most other fans to not be very good, which is that you have to get on with actually making them at some point, and there is not really that much good reason to exceed the requirements set.  That would be ASHRAE 241 for the amount of clean air we need in a classroom and other buildings,and ANSI S12.60, for noise in classrooms (hospital wards and other spaces have similar standards which have mostly similar values anyway). This fan can already be used to make an appliance that can do that with only one fan, while everything else is a long way away from that.  Thus I terminated development when it was good enough to meet the requirements.}
