\par \pard\plain \s0\sl276\slmult1\ql\aspalpha\faauto\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi0\sb0\sa0\ltrpar\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf1\striked0\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\hich\af2\dbch\af2\afs22\ai0\ab0\langfe1033\lang1033\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033{\listtext\pard\plain \cf1\ulnone\ulc0 \u9679\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls3 \li360\ri0\lin360\rin0\fi-360\tx1080\li1080\ri0\lin1080\rin0\fi-360{\lang1025\rtlch \ltrch\loch
I tried using a tpu/nylon blend to increase damping, just for the primary, but it made no difference so I went back to the previous approach. I thought it was going to help as the difference in damping between some rigid filaments did help. It might help for the secondary more, but it\'92s a little too floppy, it was 72D durometer.  85D might work ok but I couldn\'92t get any. You can have high damping while still having high stiffness, there is nothing stopping that.  It\'92s just that TPU has good damping and is usually used in elastomers.  There are some papers that describe filaments with unusually high damping but you can\'92t buy the filament of course.}
